review_blob: Tawny light brown.  Soapy, thick head, with lace.  Fruit, very gentle hop note (similar nose).  Understated sweet malt.  Dries out as it finishes ... also sours (?) as it warms.  Good for a novelty beer, but I found this otherwise very uninteresting.
beer_name: Black Sheep Monty Pythons Holy Grail (Bottle)

review_blob: Bright white, frothy head with a good last.  Dark straw colour.  Lean hoppy note, with fruit, in the nose.  Good (pale) malt, with some sweetness.  Long, lasting hop finish.  Simple, but great balence, well crafted.
UPDATED: OCT 25, 2003

Very light, flaxen colour.  Spritzy, light head, stark white.  Slightly overcarbonated, but it was bottled, so who knows.  Sweet floral nose.  Grassy hops (very distinctive), nice bitterness.  Middling sweet malt note.  Gentle, crisp mouthfeel.  No skunk in any of the bottles, and they're all green.  Guess I was lucky.

BLACK colour, frothy, thick head, lace, superb hold too.  Coffee notes (i.e. definite malt roastyness), burnt caramel, oily sweetness... where's the alcohol?  Initial fruit bite increases with warming ... delightful big beer, very mellow... although not overly complex.  Great in a Welly glass!

Fizzy, white head ... pours scarily pale, with a greenish twinge.  Adjuncty, vegetable nose.  Thin hoppiness and sweetness in finish.  Phenols (?) in there somewhere.  But it's another country on my list.

Perfect you-know-what colour (sorry, but it's true).  Thin, effervescent head, little lace, poor durability.  Yeast is predominant in the nose, with light malt underpinnings.  Yeasty, citrus, slight malt flavours... finishing with a mouth coating grain flavour.  Not bad for a hot summer's day.

Red amber, clear, lacy head... rich, sweet fruit in the nose starts out tart, but fades beautifully into a full, caramalised fruit rear, with slight malt grainy overtones.  I don't pick up any real bitterness, this is quite unique.  Again I get the sense of Christmas pudding.  Pretty good.

Cloudy, semi-opaque, rich brown, with lacy, lasting, thick head.  Toffee, plum, peaches in the nose.  Taste - plum pudding, brandy notes, treacle, a touch (?) of smoke ... with alcohol leveling the rear finish.  I found this less complex than Le Terrible, though.
Lovely, but far beyond my skills ...

Aroma is roasty liquorice, alcohol.  Like a tropical stout, but a bit dryer.  Colour's alright ... great mouthfeel, wafts about the nose.  Very sweet.  I have an old bottle (December) but still quite good.  Reminds me very much of a tropical stout.

(St. Kitts) Thick lacy head, light brown.  Black.  Rich, sweet aroma - molasses, liquorice, burnt caramel.  Alcohol aroma but no real burn... thick liquorice sweetness, sourness too.  Roast/bitterness, but more sour.  This is what Guinness is supposed to taste like!

(first cider ever) Ummm... ginger ale?  Sour apple and alcohol in the nose, no head, bubbly, sweet smelling too.  Augh.  Tastes like apple juice cut with small amounts of vodka.  Not beer, I just don't know what to say.

(Nitro Can) Penultimate of by brother's birthday present.  Copper/amber, deep colour, fake nitro head.  Roasted malt, slightly spicy hop flavour.  Very soft and tends on the watery side, although the flavours are well rounded, I suspect the widget (damn that thing) ruins most of whatever character was in here.  But drinkable, yes.  Thanks bro!

Thinish, sparkling head, pale brown.  Black - totally opaque.  Sweet, toffee and liquorice in the nose, even chilled I get alcohol burn.  Thick, sweet, alcohol and roast in the rear.  Oily.  Not nearly as nice as Caribbean Guinness FES.

Thin head, deep gold / copper twinge.  Malty, aromatic hops nose (sweet-spicy).  Sweet malty start, drying out with the same hops as the nose.  Great mouthfeel.  Citrus notes, banana (???).  My favourite with Indian Curry.

Fake nitro head, copper-brown colour.  Sour malt in the nose.  Slight bitterness on the front, slight malt ... as it warms you get a bit more mouthfeel.  I can coax a bit of hidden alcohol (wow, at 4.4%)  Very, very average ... but what can one expect but bland, one dimensional beer if the can has a widget?  I notice something harsh in there (phenols?) but I may have an old can.

(widget can) Fake creamy head, takes a while to settle.  Opaque and all that jazz.  A sweet, roasty aroma, lots of malt.  Roast on the tongue, "dead" (on account of the nitrogen?) flavour.  I used to drink Guinness and wonder what all the fuss was about ... it tastes like weak ash, no real complexity.  Now I know I was right to doubt ... 'specially the nitro can.

Dark copper ... cherry wood colour.  Uneven, slightly thinnish head.  Sweet aroma, taste ... fruity, some malt, a little bitterness here and there.  Thick.  Nothing to write home about (and I'm left a bit hollow after waiting so long to try this), but fine sipping beer.

Perfect (I mean perfect - creamy, lacy) fluffy brown head.  Dark but not opaque.
Sweet, roasty malt notes in nose.  Smooooooooth as silk ... rich roast, sweetness, a little bitterness on the finish (barely).  You could drink several litres of this stuff without much fuss.  Divine.  If only  this was available in place of Guinness!

Looks like crude oil  (completely opaque) poured, very little head... although bubbles are apparent within.  Oily/sweet malt/rye bread/brakish aroma.  Sour sweetness (not to the extent of Guinness FES), some bready/chewy malt.  Pumpernickle...Cocoa.  Very smooth mouthfeel ... some alcohol rises to nose. Sweet roast stays in the mouth ... good stuff, but a bit too thin.

Medium brown, clear, super lacey head.  Lots of smoke (mmm...bacon) and malt in the nose.  Sweet, malty, delcious rounded smoke taste, very multilayered, stays with you for a minute or two, developing ...  I can smell the fire!  Absolutely to die for.

Let"s read the notes here... I got an apple cider aroma.  Dark, rich brown colour.  Thick, lacy, creamy head.  To taste, alcohol, light yeast, empty (one dimensional) wheat malt, a little smokey.  Like Aventinus but much less complex.

(2002) Delightful cola appreance... spicey/sweet malty aroma (strange metallic note!). Smokey, caramel (fruit?), malty, a little burnt.  Slight alcohol warming, twinge of hop.      A bit oily, like a tropical stout in some ways.  Good stuff ...
I didnt like this one.  Cloudy bright copper (like a pot).  Sour plum aroma, quite sweet, a lot of alcohol in there too.  Sharp, yeasty type sweetness, alcohol warmth ... a little sickly.

Wow, cloudy red wine with a pink head... no, thats just what it looked like.  Sweet, sour (i.e. like raspberries) - very sudden though.  Not tart.  May have had a slight malt twinge at the end.  Not really a beer, but good nonetheless.
Empty is the word that first comes to mind.  Even worse than regular Carib - slight hops, very grainy ... zero complexity.  No one should drink this beer if Caribs around.

Can:
Nice hops, with a gentle nudge of malt in there.  Nice off brown/golden colour.  I didnt get much head out of the can, but thats always more of a visual thing, isnt it?

(St. Kitts incarnation)
After you try Stag, youll come running to this beer, even if it is entirely forgettable.  Slight bitterness in finish (IBU would be the same as Steamwhistle). Some plastic.  Grainy.  Light golden, clear colour that screams boring.

NITRO CAN...  
Thus the taste was a one dimensional roast. Fake creamy head.  A little bit of sweetness that brings a tropical stout to mind.

I didnt like this one very much (I have a bias against wits for some reason).  Spicy aroma. Lemon/pepper with hints of yeast.  Effervescent (?) - too carbonated.  I couldnt catch much of this "complexity", perhaps I was drinking it too cold.

Light, frothy head.  Looks like carbonated apple juice.  Sweet/sour smell... like apple juice, but with a hint of malt.  Yeasty taste... a bit sweet, not much else, a little bitterness hidden behind it.  Easy drinking but not a repeat.  The alcohol is very well hidden - not detectable at all.

Thick, shallow head, dissipates rather quickly.    Sweet, oily aroma.  OPAQUE, and I mean I cant see the halogen bulb through this stuff.  Sweet, toffee, rich malty goodness... slight bitterness at the very end.  Very drinkable, although not at all a typical stout.
Lacey head, brown/off-red colour, cloudy.  Sediment!  Yeasty.  Light hops, very dry finish.  Sweet (fruit?) flavours.  I found this rather one dimensional.  Damn gift pack!
Nice, solid head, good colour.  Aroma is very strong metallic hops.  Taste is similar but with lots of roasty malt.  Good but not what I would expect from these guys.
Oh my god!  This is what pilsner is truly meant to be.  Almost like a Denisons Weisse (hey, list what you know), but much more hops and considerably more complex in the finish.

My overall comment would be "extraordinarily ordinary".  The flavour is *empty* until you get some simple malt at the end.  Nice lacey head, but the colour puts me off a tad.  Couldnt get much of a smell out of it either.  Good with food, not a standalone.

Great head, very nice unfiltered colour (golden brown, cloudy).  Citrus yeast aroma.  No front to the taste, sour/yeast middle, and my favourite, a yeasty/nutty/bread like finish.  I was wrong, Denisons is better than this.  Otherwise, good, a bit better than Paulaner.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: Nice, light brown head, pretty solid.  Dark caramel colour (almost opaque!).  Sweet, yeasty/spicey aroma.  Taste is like a nice, fuzzy hug...  banana, strong clove, wheat malt on the end.  No alcohol on the nose when cold, but comes through strongly as it warms.  Excellent!
UPDATED: JAN 19, 2003
UPDATED: NOV 5, 2003
This is neither crap, nor good, beer.  Unlike the other green bottles they serve at clubs, though, there is a slight bitter finish to let you know you got something for your 5$.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: Lovely colour, yeasty/spicey aroma, starts slightly sour.  A little too much carbonation.  Banana/clove aroma through the middle.  Hops on the finish, leaving a pleasant sour/bitter impression.  I always get a hint of smoke in here, am I wrong?
While I suspect my palate is unrefined, I simply couldnt get much beyond a simple wit here.  Try as I might, I cant taste more than a tiny hint of spice/orange.  Otherwise good.
Good overall, but beyond the initial nice impression it doesnt have much to hide.
